True leadership is percolative and touches every individual, not just the mercantile class.It is obsessed with equality of opportunity so that every Kenyan child gets a fair share. I want to explain to you, from my perspective, why we remain poor, even though our environment has great potential and what we need to do to change our fortunes.
In my village, there is a teacher and community leader called Bob Mwirigi. Older people know him as Mwirigi wa Ciokibise. I have to warn you that there is dense cultural, tribal and linguistic complexity in that last name. Like raw honey, it is viscous, sticky, almost impenetrable. My people speak five mutually intelligible dialect clusters: Tharaka, Chuka, Mwimbi, Imenti and Igembe/Tigania, roughly corresponding to the sub-tribes of the Meru.



