The “S” in some parts of Imenti Central is not the sibilant described by modern linguistics; it is a more primieval and exotic affair which might give me a PhD one day, Inshallah, if some snot-nosed kid has not beaten me to it. But I digress.
Some 50 years ago, Bob, now a retired TTC lecturer and teacher, and other educated members of the community formed an organisation to promote education in the village and held an annual prize-giving day, awarding top pupils and schools. It’s active, though my participation has been shamefully poor. It provided a loose network of support for young people. 
Without that network and Bob, I probably would never have become a journalist. First, Bob had more books that any other person in the sub-location in an age when books were the main source of knowledge.
Secondly, he was deeply interested in young people and helping them to build their careers. So, when I wanted to apply to the School of Journalism at the University of Nairobi, I, naturally went to see Bob. I can’t remember whether he got me something to read but he put me in touch with Dr Gerrishon Ikiara, a leader of that association and then a senior lecturer at the Department of Economics.



