I came to Nairobi to see Dr Ikiara, who had arranged for me to see yet another lecturer who had taught the course at the school and could answer the question I had carried for 250km: How does one become a journalist in Kenya?
I found Dr Ikiara a very smart man. From a communications perspective, he was like Lenin, with an accent. Big brain, very verbal. The genius of Lenin (and I am speaking from old memory) was his ability to explain Marxism to peasants, reducing complex philosophy into morsels that they could eat.
True leadership 
I was also struck by Ikiara’s access to new information, to fresh data from research which made his scholarship current. I met other economists, I think Dr Manundu and a brilliant one who became a Sunday Nation columnist and an arrogant public intellectual who nowadays does not recognise me when we meet in the mall. Which is fine, let me tell you Maina, because I don’t recognise him also. 



