He said I was reducing journalism to a “debating club” which risked formenting revolution and turning the country into “a Bosnia”, which sounded all the more effective when he rendered it in our accent as “a mbosnia”. Being a fiery young man with ideas of my own who knew a couple of societies which could have benefitted from a revolution, I was unmoved.
But when he was done dressing me down and we sat down to have discussion, he taught me lessons that have been with me all these years. Then, the Narc government was quite fanatical about mid-level colleges. Admission was devolved to districts and each was given a quota with a massive attempt at ensuring that admission was fair.
“When a child is admitted to a college and becomes a teacher or a nurse, he or she changes the fortunes not just of the individual but the whole family and community,” I recall him telling me. 
During the Moi state, admission to these colleges was part of the largesse dispensed by the corrupt patronage system.
Here is my point: We need true, passionate leadership to change the lives of our people. True leadership is an accelerator of potential, not just a writer of constitutions.
Humble Bob has helped to transform the lives of hundreds of young people; the Constitution writers have only transformed their own lives and those of their relatives.



